<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n50081a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n50" href="#n50081a">N50 (VI.B.37)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n50all.htm#n50081a"> 81(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> triangular shields</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">It is also related by Giraldus Cambrensis that the Irish procured their battle-axes from the Northmen. The Danes in England, at least towards the latter part of their sway, are likewise said to have used shirts of mail, or chain armour, in which, however, the rings were not interlaced, but sewed on by the side of each other; helmets, with iron bands that covered the nose; and lastly, large pointed <mark>triangular shields</mark>. <small> J.J.A. Worsaae, <a name="JJAW2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JJAW2"><cite title="source">An Account of the Danes and Norwegians in England, Scotland and Ireland</cite></a> (1852) 46</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
